      <details>
        <summary>What is a growth stock?</summary>
        <p>A growth stock is a share in a company that is expected to grow its sales and earnings at a rate significantly faster than the market average, usually by reinvesting all profits back into the business.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do growth stocks pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>Typically, no. Growth companies prefer to reinvest their cash into research and development, hiring, and expansion rather than paying it out to shareholders as dividends.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why are growth stocks so expensive?</summary>
        <p>They often appear expensive (trading at high Price-to-Earnings ratios) because investors are paying for the company's future potential. They expect the company to be much larger and more profitable years down the line.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are growth stocks risky?</summary>
        <p>Yes, they are generally more volatile and riskier than value or dividend stocks. If a growth company fails to meet the market's high expectations for revenue growth, its stock price can drop dramatically.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How are growth stocks affected by interest rates?</summary>
        <p>Growth stocks are highly sensitive to interest rates. When interest rates rise, the present value of the company's future earnings decreases, and borrowing money for expansion becomes more expensive, which often causes growth stock prices to fall.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
